x4freetext: Main ref.
-Measurement of double-differential (N,a) cross sec-
tions of Fe, Ni, Cu and 50-Cr for 4.5 - 14.1 MeV
neutrons.
M.B., N.I., I.M., S.M., N.H. And dynamitron
measurements.
S.C., T.F., M.M., K.H., S.M. And tandem
measurements.
The Tohoku University 4.5 MV dyna-
mitron accelerator, and
The JAERI 20 MV tandem accelerator
.Neutrons were produced by the following reactions
En = 7.6 MeV.
En = 11.5 MeV.
En = 14.1 MeV.
.The energy spreads were 0.1 - 0.4 MeV.
Simultaneous registration of the anode and
cathode signals gave two-dimensional spectra with
information on charged-particle energy and emission
angle.
A Frisch-grided ionization chamber was used. It
had a length of 104 mm and a diameter of 140 mm. It
contained a common cathode plane and two anode planes.
The electrodes were made of tantalum and tungsten to
reduce background. The samples were mounted in a
remotely controlled sample changer. The detector was
filled with a mixture of krypton gas and about 3
percent CO-2 or C-H4. The pressure was adjusted to
stop the type of particle under study, and were in the
range 2.8 - 12.5 atm. The operational electric field
was around 0.5 V/cm/torr.
A 2 X 2 inch Ne213 detector was used to monitor
the source neutrons, for normalization between runs.
A proton recoil telescope was used to determine
the absolute neutron flux at 14.1 MeV.
The data were normalized using
the well-known Np scattering cross section.
.The samples were metallic foils of natural iron,
nickel, copper and isotopically enriched chromium-50.
They were 25 mm in diameter with thicknesses around
3 - 4 micrometers. In addition, a 10 micrometer thick
polypropylene sample was used for neutron flux and
energy scale determination. For sample-out measure-
ments, a 50 micrometer thick tungsten foil was used.
.The data were corrected for background by subtracting
sample-out spectra. The data were further corrected
for background due to (N,P) reactions and parasitic
source neutrons, and for energy loss within the
sample.
.Angle-integrated spectra and production cross sections
were deduced from the double-differential data.

x4freetext: The errors given include contributions from
statistics, 3 - 30 percent, absolute normalization,
3 - 6 percent, extrapolation of alpha-yields, 3 - 6
percent, and background correction, 1 - 3 percent.
